            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kevin Reilly\u2019s roots are firmly planted in the fog-dusted soil of the Bay Area. Raised in a working-class Irish-American family in Daly City, he grew up seeing San Francisco not as a hub of tech innovation, but as the city on the skyline where his father, a union carpenter, went to work. Kevin was an unremarkable student, more interested in garage bands than grade point averages. After high school, he drifted through a series of retail and food service jobs, feeling a growing sense of aimlessness.\n\nThe turning point came when his beloved grandmother suffered a stroke. During her final year in a long-term care facility, Kevin witnessed the profound impact of the Certified Nursing Assistants. They were the ones who provided the daily, hands-on care with a blend of professional skill and genuine compassion that the harried doctors and nurses often couldn't. Inspired, Kevin enrolled in a CNA certification program at a local community college, finally finding a calling that felt tangible and important.\n\nNow 34, Kevin lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond. His daily routine is dictated by his shifts at a geriatric care center near Golden Gate Park. He wakes before sunrise, brews strong coffee, and catches the Muni bus for his 2.5-mile commute. His days are a blur of assisting residents with bathing, dressing, and eating; of listening to stories from decades past; and of offering a steadying hand or a patient ear. The work is physically demanding and emotionally draining, but it provides a deep sense of purpose that his earlier jobs lacked.\n\nHis social life is centered around a tight-knit group of friends, many of whom also work in healthcare. They decompress over cheap beer and trivia nights at a neighborhood pub or gather for potlucks. Though his $58,000 salary makes life in San Francisco a constant exercise in budgeting, he finds joy in the city\u2019s simple pleasures: a long run through the park, a carnitas burrito from his favorite taqueria in the Mission, the quiet camaraderie of his commute.\n\nKevin dreams of one day going back to school to become a Registered Nurse, but the financial and academic hurdles feel immense. For now, he focuses on being the best CNA he can be, providing dignity to the city's elderly. He is a quiet, essential thread in the fabric of San Francisco, a caregiver who supports the generations that built the city he calls home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 25, watching a CNA named Carmen gently braid his grandmother\u2019s thin, silver hair. His grandmother, silenced by the stroke, just stared ahead, but Carmen hummed softly. In that moment, watching Carmen\u2019s gentle, practiced hands, Kevin felt a wave of shame for his own driftless life, followed by a sudden, sharp clarity. It wasn\u2019t about heroics; it was about this quiet act of dignity. He enrolled in his certification course the following week, finally seeing a path that felt real and necessary.\n\n***\n\n2.\nA few months into his first job, a resident named Mr. Chen, a former tailor, was agitated and refused to eat. None of the usual tricks worked. Kevin noticed the fine stitching on Mr. Chen\u2019s old sweater and simply asked about it. The old man\u2019s eyes focused. For ten minutes, they talked about fabrics and seams. Then, Mr. Chen quietly picked up his spoon. It taught Kevin his most vital skill: to always look for the person hiding inside the patient, the one with a life and a craft.\n\n***\n\n3.\nLast year, after a brutal double shift where he lost a resident he\u2019d cared for for years, he met his friends at their usual pub. He felt hollowed out, unable to even explain the depth of his exhaustion. His friend Maria, an ER tech, didn\u2019t ask questions. She just pushed a glass of beer toward him and, when the trivia host asked a question about 80s music, she nudged him. That small, wordless gesture of shared understanding kept him from shattering.\n\n***\n\n4.\nOn a Tuesday a few weeks ago, after a difficult day, he didn't take the bus. He just ran. He ran through Golden Gate Park as the fog rolled in, the scent of eucalyptus and damp earth washing away the scent of antiseptic and sickness. His lungs burned and his legs ached, but with every stride, he felt the day\u2019s weight dissolving. This was his therapy, his freedom, a reminder that his body was still his own. It was how he reclaimed himself.\n\n***\n\n5.\nHe\u2019ll never forget helping Mr. Henderson, a retired ironworker, to the window last month. The old man pointed a trembling finger toward the downtown skyline. \u201cHelped put the steel up on that one,\u201d he\u2019d rasped. Kevin looked at the distant skyscraper, thinking of his father\u2019s own calloused hands, and felt a profound connection. His dad built the city\u2019s bones, and he was here, caring for its heart. It made him feel, for the first time, like he truly belonged here."
